/*In Java, you can take input from the user using the Scanner class,
 which is part of the java.util package. Here's a step-by-step example:

Import the Scanner class:
import java.util.Scanner;

Create a Scanner object:
You need to create an instance of Scanner and link it to System.in 
to read from the standard input.

Use the appropriate method for the type of input:
The Scanner class provides methods like 
 */



 //# next()

Reads a single word (until a whitespace) as a String.
 If you enter "Hello World", next() will read only "Hello".
Example:

import java.util.*;
public class practice{
    public static void main(String args[]){
        Scanner sc = new Scanner(System.in);

        String name = sc.next();
        System.out.println(name);
    }
}

input = arun kumar
output your entered value = arun




//nextLine()

Reads the entire line as a String (including spaces).
If you enter "Hello World", nextLine() will read "Hello World".
Example: 

 import java.util.*;
 public class practice{
    public static void main(String args[]){
        Scanner sc = new Scanner(System.in);
        String name = sc.nextLine();
        System.out.println(name);
    }
 }
input = arun kumar
output your entered value = arun kumar





//nextInt()

Reads an integer (whole number).
 Input 42 → returns int value 42.
Example:

import java.util.*;
public class practice{
    public static void main(String args[]){
        Scanner sc = new Scanner(System.in);
        int a = sc.nextInt();
        System.out.println(a);

    }
}
input = 123 456
output your entered value = 123





//nextDouble()

Reads a double (decimal number).
 Input 3.14 → returns double value 3.14.
Example:

import java.util.*;
public class practice{
    public static void main(String args []){
        Scanner sc = new Scanner(System.in);
        double b = sc.nextDouble();
        System.out.println(b);
    }
}
input = 123.123 12
output your entered value = 123.123





//nextBoolean()

Reads a boolean value (true or false).
 Input true or false → returns boolean value true or false.
Example:

import java.util.Scanner;
public class practice{
    public static void main(String args []){
        Scanner sc = new Scanner(System.in);
        boolean value = sc.nextBoolean();
        System.out.println(value);

    }
}
input = true
output your entered value = true
